            ['title' => 'Quran as Lullaby: Surah Al-Baqarah',  'emoji' => '☪️', 'age_tier' => 'baby', 'subject' => 'quran',     'age_min' => 0,    'age_max' => 2.0,  'is_free' => true,  'duration' => 20, 'activity_type' => 'vocal',       'skill' => 'Quran phoneme exposure',           'description' => 'For parents: Play or recite Surah Al-Baqarah softly during baby\'s sleep time. The Prophet ﷺ said that Surah Al-Baqarah protects the home from Shaytan. Exposure to Quranic Arabic from birth imprints the rhythm and phonemes of the Quran into the auditory memory — the foundation of future Quran fluency.'],
            ['title' => 'Ayat Al-Kursi Before Sleep',           'emoji' => '🌙', 'age_tier' => 'baby', 'subject' => 'quran',     'age_min' => 0,    'age_max' => 2.0,  'is_free' => true,  'duration' => 5,  'activity_type' => 'vocal',       'skill' => 'Prophetic sunnah protection',      'description' => 'For parents: Recite Ayat Al-Kursi (2:255) over your sleeping baby each night, gently blowing on their face. This follows the sunnah of the Prophet ﷺ who taught that this verse provides special protection. It also creates a deeply calming bedtime ritual tied to Islamic identity from birth.'],
            ['title' => 'Bismillah Before Every Feed',          'emoji' => '🍼', 'age_tier' => 'baby', 'subject' => 'quran',     'age_min' => 0,    'age_max' => 2.0,  'is_free' => true,  'duration' => 2,  'activity_type' => 'routine',     'skill' => 'Dhikr habit formation',            'description' => 'For parents: Say "Bismillah" clearly before every breastfeed, bottle, or food introduction. The habit of beginning every action with the name of Allah is a prophetic sunnah that should be established from the very first days of life. Baby learns to associate feeding with this blessed word.'],
            ['title' => 'Al-Fatiha Morning Recitation',         'emoji' => '🌅', 'age_tier' => 'baby', 'subject' => 'quran',     'age_min' => 0,    'age_max' => 2.0,  'is_free' => true,  'duration' => 5,  'activity_type' => 'vocal',       'skill' => 'Surah memorisation exposure',      'description' => 'For parents: Recite Surah Al-Fatiha slowly and clearly to baby every morning while making eye contact. Al-Fatiha is the opening chapter of the Quran, repeated in every prayer — early daily exposure means baby will be hearing the surah thousands of times before they are old enough to consciously memorise it.'],
            ['title' => 'Surah Al-Ikhlas as Daily Dhikr',       'emoji' => '✨', 'age_tier' => 'baby', 'subject' => 'quran',     'age_min' => 0,    'age_max' => 2.0,  'is_free' => true,  'duration' => 3,  'activity_type' => 'vocal',       'skill' => 'Tawheed concept exposure',         'description' => 'For parents: Recite Surah Al-Ikhlas (just 4 verses) three times daily to baby. The Prophet ﷺ described it as equivalent in reward to a third of the Quran. Its short, rhythmic verses are among the easiest for children to memorise and introduce the foundational concept of Allah\'s oneness.'],
            ['title' => 'Surah Al-Falaq Evening Protection',    'emoji' => '🛡️','age_tier' => 'baby', 'subject' => 'quran',     'age_min' => 0,    'age_max' => 2.0,  'is_free' => true,  'duration' => 3,  'activity_type' => 'vocal',       'skill' => 'Prophetic protective adhkar',      'description' => 'For parents: Recite Surah Al-Falaq and Surah An-Nas each evening, then gently blow over baby. Abu Dawud and others narrate the Prophet ﷺ recited these before sleep. Establishing these as the nightly protective routine creates a lifelong Islamic bedtime habit.'],
            ['title' => 'Surah An-Nas Morning Protection',      'emoji' => '🌤️','age_tier' => 'baby', 'subject' => 'quran',     'age_min' => 0,    'age_max' => 2.0,  'is_free' => true,  'duration' => 3,  'activity_type' => 'vocal',       'skill' => 'Morning adhkar foundation',        'description' => 'For parents: Recite Surah An-Nas three times each morning, blowing over baby afterward. Consistency in morning and evening adhkar builds an Islamic temporal rhythm into baby\'s earliest days — spiritually grounding the household routine.'],
            ['title' => 'Family Dhikr Circle: Baby Present',    'emoji' => '🤲', 'age_tier' => 'baby', 'subject' => 'quran',     'age_min' => 0.5,  'age_max' => 2.0,  'is_free' => false, 'duration' => 10, 'activity_type' => 'routine',     'skill' => 'Islamic family culture',           'description' => 'For parents: Include baby in family dhikr circles — gather as a family after Fajr or Asr and recite Subhanallah, Alhamdulillah, Allahu Akbar. Babies absorb the emotional and spiritual atmosphere of their household. Including them normalises dhikr as a natural family activity from the beginning.'],
            ['title' => 'Azan at Birth and Milestones',         'emoji' => '🕌', 'age_tier' => 'baby', 'subject' => 'quran',     'age_min' => 0,    'age_max' => 0.5,  'is_free' => false, 'duration' => 5,  'activity_type' => 'routine',     'skill' => 'Islamic rites of passage',         'description' => 'For parents: Recite the Azan softly in baby\'s right ear at birth (as per sunnah) and also at major milestones (first tooth, first steps). The first sound Allah\'s name and the call to prayer is a prophetic tradition that establishes Islamic identity from the very first moments of earthly life.'],
            ['title' => 'Dua When Baby Cries: Al-Mu\'awwidhatain', 'emoji' => '📿','age_tier' => 'baby', 'subject' => 'quran',    'age_min' => 0,    'age_max' => 2.0,  'is_free' => false, 'duration' => 3,  'activity_type' => 'vocal',       'skill' => 'Dua as comfort tool',             'description' => 'For parents: When baby cries and you feel helpless, recite softly "Bismillahi arqeeka, min kulli shay\'in yu\'dheeka" (I ruqyah you in the name of Allah from everything that harms you) followed by Al-Mu\'awwidhatain. This is a sunnah ruqyah for babies and reminds parents to turn to Allah first.'],
            ['title' => 'Soft Quran Background During Play',    'emoji' => '🎵', 'age_tier' => 'baby', 'subject' => 'quran',     'age_min' => 0,    'age_max' => 2.0,  'is_free' => false, 'duration' => 30, 'activity_type' => 'observation', 'skill' => 'Passive Quran phoneme absorption', 'description' => 'For parents: Play soft, clear Quran recitation in the background during daytime play — not as entertainment but as environmental immersion. Choose clear, melodious recitations at conversational volume. Early phoneme exposure creates an "auditory template" that facilitates Quran recitation later.'],
            ['title' => 'Dua Before Sleep: Parent\'s Version',  'emoji' => '😴', 'age_tier' => 'baby', 'subject' => 'quran',     'age_min' => 0,    'age_max' => 2.0,  'is_free' => false, 'duration' => 5,  'activity_type' => 'vocal',       'skill' => 'Sleep dua habit',                  'description' => 'For parents: After placing baby down, recite: "Allahumma bismika amutu wa ahya" (O Allah, in Your name I die and I live). Model it out loud so baby hears it. By toddlerhood they will begin to say it after you — habits established in the first two years are the most enduring of a lifetime.'],
            ['title' => 'Islamic Nasheed Lullabies',            'emoji' => '🌙', 'age_tier' => 'baby', 'subject' => 'quran',     'age_min' => 0,    'age_max' => 2.0,  'is_free' => false, 'duration' => 15, 'activity_type' => 'vocal',       'skill' => 'Islamic identity and calm',        'description' => 'For parents: Use vocal, a cappella nasheeds (no instruments) as calming music. There are beautiful Arabic nasheeds about the Prophet ﷺ and praise of Allah composed specifically for children. These provide the emotional warmth of music within Islamic guidelines, associating Islamic content with comfort and love.'],
            ['title' => 'Hasbunallahu wa Ni\'mal Wakeel: Daily Dua', 'emoji' => '🤲','age_tier' => 'baby', 'subject' => 'quran', 'age_min' => 0,    'age_max' => 2.0,  'is_free' => false, 'duration' => 3,  'activity_type' => 'vocal',       'skill' => 'Tawakkul concept introduction',    'description' => 'For parents: Recite "Hasbunallahu wa ni\'mal wakeel" (Allah is sufficient for us, and He is the best Disposer of affairs) regularly — when baby is unwell, at difficult moments, as a reassurance. Baby absorbs the emotional calm that accompanies this dua and the concept that trust is placed in Allah above all else.'],

